That is, the result is of the form: Some(f(...f(f(k1, v1, k2, v2), k3, v3)..., kn, vn))

Returns None if m is the empty map.

def reduceRight[v, ef, ef, k](f: v -> (v -> v & ef \ ef'), m: Map[k, v]): Option[v] & ef

Applies f to all values in m going from right to left until a single value v is obtained. Returns Some(v).

That is, the result is of the form: Some(f(v1, ...f(vn-2, f(vn-1, vn))...))

Returns None if m is the empty map.

def reduceRightWithKey[k, v, ef, ef](f: k -> (v -> (k -> (v -> (k, v) & ef \ ef'))), m: Map[k, v]): Option[(k, v)] & ef

Applies f to all mappings in m going from right to left until a single mapping (k, v) is obtained. Returns Some((k, v)).

That is, the result is of the form: Some(f(k1, v1, ...f(kn-2, vn-2, f(kn-1, vn-1, kn, vn))...))

Returns None if m is the empty map.

def remove[k, v](k: k, m: Map[k, v]): Map[k, v] & true with Order[k]

Removes the mapping k from the map m.

def sequence[k, m, v](m: Map[k, m[v]]): m[Map[k, v]] & true with Applicative[m]

Returns the result of running all the actions in the map m.

def singleton[k, v](k: k, v: v): Map[k, v] & true with Order[k]

Returns the singleton map where key k is mapped to value v.

Map#{k => v} is syntactic sugar for singleton (Map#{k => v} = singleton(k, v)).

def size[k, v](m: Map[k, v]): Int32 & true

Returns the size of m.

def sumKeys[v](m: Map[Int32, v]): Int32 & true

Returns the sum of all keys in the map m.

def sumValues[k](m: Map[k, Int32]): Int32 & true

Returns the sum of all values in the map m.

@ParallelWhenPure
def sumWith[k, v, ef, ef](f: k -> (v -> Int32 & ef \ ef'), m: Map[k, v]): Int32 & ef

Returns the sum of all key-value pairs k => v in the map m according to the function f.

Purity reflective: Runs in parallel when given a pure function f.

def toChain[a, b](m: Map[a, b]): Chain[(a, b)] & true with Order[a]

Returns the map m as a chain of key-value pairs.

def toDelayList[k, v](m: Map[k, v]): DelayList[(k, v)] & true

Returns the map m as a DelayList of key-value pairs.

def toDelayMap[k, v](m: Map[k, v]): DelayMap[k, v] & true

Returns m as a DelayMap.

def toList[k, v](m: Map[k, v]): List[(k, v)] & true

Returns the map m as a list of key-value pairs.

def toMultiMap[k, v](m: Map[k, v]): MultiMap[k, v] & true with Order[k], Order[v]

Returns a MultiMap where key k is mapped to the singleton set containing v.

def toMutDeque[r, k, v](r: Region[r], m: Map[k, v]): MutDeque[(k, v), r] & r

Returns m as a MutDeque.

def toMutMap[r, k, v](r: Region[r], m: Map[k, v]): MutMap[k, v, r] & r

Returns m as a mutable set.

def toSet[k, v](m: Map[k, v]): Set[(k, v)] & true with Order[k], Order[v]

Returns the map m as a set of key-value pairs.

def toString[k, v](m: Map[k, v]): String & true with ToString[k], ToString[v]

Returns a string representation of the given map m.

def traverse[v1, ef, ef, m, v2, k](f: v1 -> m[v2] & ef \ ef', m: Map[k, v1]): m[Map[k, v2]] & ef with Applicative[m]

Returns the result of applying the applicative mapping function f to all the values of the map m.

def traverseWithKey[k, v1, ef, ef, m, v2](f: k -> (v1 -> m[v2] & ef \ ef'), m: Map[k, v1]): m[Map[k, v2]] & ef with Applicative[m]

Returns the result of applying the applicative mapping function f to all the key-value pairs of the map m.

def unfold[s, ef, ef, k, v](f: s -> Option[(k, v, s)] & ef \ ef', st: s): Map[k, v] & ef with Order[k]

Build a map by applying f to the seed value st.

f should return Some(k,v,st1) to signal a new key-value pair k and v and a new seed value st1.

f should return None to signal the end of building the map.

def unfoldWithIter[ef, ef, k, v](next: Unit -> Option[(k, v)] & ef \ ef'): Map[k, v] & ef with Order[k]

Build a map by applying the function next to (). next is expected to encapsulate a stateful resource such as a file handle that can be iterated.

next should return Some(k,v) to signal a new key-value pair k and v.

next should return None to signal the end of building the map.

def union[k, v](m1: Map[k, v], m2: Map[k, v]): Map[k, v] & true with Order[k]

Returns the left-biased union of m1 and m2.

That is, key collisions are resolved by taking the mapping from m1.

def unionWith[v, ef, ef, k](f: v -> (v -> v & ef \ ef'), m1: Map[k, v], m2: Map[k, v]): Map[k, v] & ef with Order[k]

Returns the union of m1 and m2 where key collisions are resolved with the merge function f.

def unionWithKey[k, v, ef, ef](f: k -> (v -> (v -> v & ef \ ef')), m1: Map[k, v], m2: Map[k, v]): Map[k, v] & ef with Order[k]

Returns the union of m1 and m2 where key collisions are resolved with the merge function f, taking both the key and values.

def update[v, ef, ef, k](f: v -> Option[v] & ef \ ef', k: k, m: Map[k, v]): Map[k, v] & ef with Order[k]

Updates m with k => v1 if k => v is in m and f(v) = Some(v1). Otherwise, returns m.

def updateWithKey[k, v, ef, ef](f: k -> (v -> Option[v] & ef \ ef'), k: k, m: Map[k, v]): Map[k, v] & ef with Order[k]

Updates m with k => v1 if k => v is in m and f(k, v) = Some(v1). Otherwise, returns m.

def valuesOf[k, v](m: Map[k, v]): List[v] & true

Returns the values of m.

Monad

Definitions

def <=<[b, ef1, ef1, m, c, a, ef2, ef2](f1: b -> m[c] & ef1 \ ef1', f2: a -> m[b] & ef2 \ ef2'): a -> m[c] & ef1 and ef2 \ {ef1', ef2'} & true with Monad[m]

<=< is an operator alias for kleisliRight.

def =<<[a, ef, ef, m, b](k: a -> m[b] & ef \ ef', x: m[a]): m[b] & ef with Monad[m]

=<< is an operator alias for flatMap.

def >=>[a, ef1, ef1, m, b, ef2, ef2, c](f1: a -> m[b] & ef1 \ ef1', f2: b -> m[c] & ef2 \ ef2'): a -> m[c] & ef1 and ef2 \ {ef1', ef2'} & true with Monad[m]

>=> is an operator alias for kleisliLeft.

def >>=[m, a, ef, ef, b](x: m[a], k: a -> m[b] & ef \ ef'): m[b] & ef with Monad[m]

>>= is the operator =<< with its arguments flipped.

>>= is the monadic bind operator.

def flatten[m, a](x: m[m[a]]): m[a] & true with Monad[m]

The monadic join operator. Flatten x - a monadic action nested in an outer monadic layer - to a single layer.

E.g. for the Option monad: flatten(Some(Some(1))) becomes Some(1).

def kleisliLeft[a, ef1, ef1, m, b, ef2, ef2, c](f1: a -> m[b] & ef1 \ ef1', f2: b -> m[c] & ef2 \ ef2', x: a): m[c] & ef1 and ef2 with Monad[m]

The left-to-right Kleisli composition operator for monads.

Map x with the monadic function f1 and then map its result with the function f2.

def kleisliRight[b, ef1, ef1, m, c, a, ef2, ef2](f1: b -> m[c] & ef1 \ ef1', f2: a -> m[b] & ef2 \ ef2', x: a): m[c] & ef1 and ef2 with Monad[m]

The right-to-left Kleisli composition operator for monads.

Map x with the monadic function f2 and then map its result with the function f1.

def fold[f, a](f: f[a]): a & true with Foldable[f], Monoid[a]

Returns the result of applying combine to all the elements in t, using empty as the initial value.

Alias for findLeft.

Optionally returns the first mapping of m that satisfies the predicate f when searching from left to right.

Optionally returns the first mapping of m that satisfies the predicate f when searching from right to left.

def foldLeft[b, v, ef, ef, k](f: b -> (v -> b & ef \ ef'), s: b, m: MultiMap[k, v]): b & ef

Applies f to a start value s and all values in m going from left to right.

That is, the result is of the form: f(...f(f(s, v1), v2)..., vn).

def foldLeftWithKey[b, k, v, ef, ef](f: b -> (k -> (v -> b & ef \ ef')), s: b, m: MultiMap[k, v]): b & ef

Applies f to a start value s and all key-value pairs in m going from left to right.

That is, the result is of the form: f(...f(f(s, k1, v1), k2, v2)..., vn).

def foldRight[v, b, ef, ef, k](f: v -> (b -> b & ef \ ef'), s: b, m: MultiMap[k, v]): b & ef

Applies f to a start value s and all values in m going from right to left.

That is, the result is of the form: f(v1, ...f(vn-1, f(vn, s))).

def foldRightWithCont[v, ef, ef, b, k](f: v -> ((Unit -> b & ef \ ef') -> b & ef \ ef'), z: b, m: MultiMap[k, v]): b & ef

Applies f to a start value z and all values in m going from right to left.

That is, the result is of the form: f(v1, ...f(vn-1, f(vn, z))). A foldRightWithCont allows early termination by not calling the continuation.

def foldRightWithKey[k, v, b, ef, ef](f: k -> (v -> (b -> b & ef \ ef')), s: b, m: MultiMap[k, v]): b & ef

Applies f to a start value s and all key-value pairs in m going from right to left.

That is, the result is of the form: f(k1, v1, ...f(kn-1, vn-1, f(kn, vn, s))).

def foldRightWithKeyCont[k, v, ef, ef, b](f: k -> (v -> ((Unit -> b & ef \ ef') -> b & ef \ ef')), z: b, m: MultiMap[k, v]): b & ef

Applies f to a start value z and all key-value pairs in m going from right to left.

That is, the result is of the form: f(k1, v1, ...f(kn-1, vn-1, f(kn, vn, z))). A foldRightWithKeyCont allows early termination by not calling the continuation.

That is, the result is of the form: f(...f(f(s, x1), x2)..., xn).

That is, the result is of the form: f(x1, ...f(xn-1, f(xn, s))...).

def foldRightWithCont[a, ef, ef, r, b](f: a -> ((Unit -> b & ef and r \ ef') -> b & ef and r \ ef'), s: b, d: MutDeque[a, r]): b & ef and r

Applies f to a start value z and all elements in d going from right to left.

That is, the result is of the form: f(x1, ...f(xn-1, f(xn, z))...). A foldRightWithCont allows early termination by not calling the continuation.

def append![m, a, r](m: m[a], v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r with Foldable[m]

Appends m to v i.e. inserts all elements from m into the end of v.

def clear![a, r](v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r

Removes all elements from the given mutable list v.

def compress![a, r](v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r

Compresses the given mutable list v if needed.

The mutable list will be shrunk to 1/2 of its size if the load factor is less than 1/4.

def copy[a, r](v: MutList[a, r]): MutList[a, r] & r

Returns a shallow copy of the given mutable list v. The capacity of the copy is equal to the length of the list.

def count[a, ef, ef, r](f: a -> Bool & ef \ ef', v: MutList[a, r]): Int32 & ef and r

Returns the number of elements in the given mutable list v that satisfies the given predicate f.

Returns 0 if the given mutable list v is empty.

def exists[a, ef, ef, r](f: a -> Bool & ef \ ef', v: MutList[a, r]): Bool & ef and r

Returns true if the given predicate f holds for at least one element of the given mutable list v.

Returns false if the given mutable list v is empty.

def find[a, r](f: a -> Bool, v: MutList[a, r]): Option[a] & r

Alias for findLeft.

def findLeft[a, r](f: a -> Bool, v: MutList[a, r]): Option[a] & r

Optionally returns the left-most element in the given mutable list v that satisfies the given predicate f.

Returns None if no element satisfies the given predicate f. Returns None if the given mutable list v is empty.

def findRight[a, r](f: a -> Bool, v: MutList[a, r]): Option[a] & r

Optionally returns the right-most element in the given mutable list v that satisfies the given predicate f.

Returns None if no element satisfies the given predicate f. Returns None if the given mutable list v is empty.

def foldLeft[b, a, ef, ef, r](f: b -> (a -> b & ef \ ef'), s: b, v: MutList[a, r]): b & ef and r

Applies f to a start value s and all elements in a going from left to right.

That is, the result is of the form: f(...f(f(s, a[0]), a[1])..., xn).

def foldMap[a, ef, ef, b, r](f: a -> b & ef \ ef', v: MutList[a, r]): b & ef and r with Monoid[b]

Returns the result of mapping each element and combining the results.

def foldRight[a, b, ef, ef, r](f: a -> (b -> b & ef \ ef'), s: b, v: MutList[a, r]): b & ef and r

Applies f to a start value s and all elements in a going from left to right.

That is, the result is of the form: f(...f(f(s, a[0]), a[1])..., xn).

The implementation is tail recursive.

def foldRightWithCont[a, ef, ef, r, b](f: a -> ((Unit -> b & ef and r \ ef') -> b & ef and r \ ef'), z: b, v: MutList[a, r]): b & ef and r

Applies f to a start value z and all elements in a going from left to right.

That is, the result is of the form: f(x1, ...f(xn-1, f(xn, z))...). A foldRightWithCont allows early termination by not calling the continuation.

def forAll[a, ef, ef, r](f: a -> Bool & ef \ ef', v: MutList[a, r]): Bool & ef and r

Returns true if the given predicate f holds for all elements of the given mutable list v.

Returns true if the given mutable list v is empty.

def forEach[a, ef, ef, r](f: a -> Unit & ef \ ef', v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & ef and r

Applies f to all the elements in v.

def forEachWithIndex[a, ef, ef, r](f: Int32 -> (a -> Unit & ef \ ef'), v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & ef and r

Applies f to all the elements in v.

def head[a, r](v: MutList[a, r]): Option[a] & r

Optionally returns the first element of the given mutable list v.

Returns None if the given mutable list v is empty.

def indexOf[a, r](x: a, v: MutList[a, r]): Option[Int32] & r with Eq[a]

Alias for IndexOfLeft

def indexOfLeft[a, r](x: a, v: MutList[a, r]): Option[Int32] & r with Eq[a]

Optionally returns the position of the first occurrence of x in v searching from left to right.

def indexOfRight[a, r](x: a, v: MutList[a, r]): Option[Int32] & r with Eq[a]

Optionally returns the position of the first occurrence of x in v searching from right to left.

def insert![a, r](x: a, i: Int32, v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r

Inserts the given element x at the given position i in the given mutable list v.

Shifts elements as necessary. Possibly expensive operation.

If the given index i exceeds the length of the mutable list, the element is inserted at the last position.

def isEmpty[a, r](v: MutList[a, r]): Bool & r

Returns true if the given mutable list v is empty.

def iterator[a, r](l: MutList[a, r]): Iterator[a, r] & r

Returns an iterator over l.

Modifying l while using an iterator has undefined behavior and is dangerous.

def join[a, r](sep: String, v: MutList[a, r]): String & r with ToString[a]

Returns the concatenation of the string representation of each element in v with sep inserted between each element.

def joinWith[a, ef, ef, r](f: a -> String & ef \ ef', sep: String, v: MutList[a, r]): String & ef and r

Returns the concatenation of the string representation of each element in v according to f with sep inserted between each element.

def last[a, r](v: MutList[a, r]): Option[a] & r

Optionally returns the last element of the given mutable list v.

Returns None if the given mutable list v is empty.

def length[a, r](v: MutList[a, r]): Int32 & r

Returns the number of elements in the given mutable list v.

def map[a, ef, ef, b, r](f: a -> b & ef \ ef', v: MutList[a, r]): MutList[b, r] & ef and r and r

Apply f to every element in v.

The result is a new mutable list.

def mapWithIndex[a, ef, ef, b, r](f: Int32 -> (a -> b & ef \ ef'), v: MutList[a, r]): MutList[b, r] & ef and r and r

Returns the result of applying f to every element in v along with that element's index.

def maximum[a, r](v: MutList[a, r]): Option[a] & r with Order[a]

Optionally finds the largest element of v according to the Order on a.

Returns None if v is empty.

def maximumBy[a, r](cmp: a -> (a -> Comparison), v: MutList[a, r]): Option[a] & r

Optionally finds the largest element of v according to the given comparator cmp.

Returns None if v is empty.

Returns true if the given element x is a member of the given mutable list v.

def minimum[a, r](v: MutList[a, r]): Option[a] & r with Order[a]

Optionally finds the smallest element of v according to the Order on a.

Returns None if v is empty.

def minimumBy[a, r](cmp: a -> (a -> Comparison), v: MutList[a, r]): Option[a] & r

Optionally finds the smallest element of v according to the given comparator cmp.

Returns None if v is empty.

def new[r, a](r: Region[r]): MutList[a, r] & r

Returns a new empty mutable list with a default capacity.

def nth[a, r](i: Int32, v: MutList[a, r]): Option[a] & r

Optionally returns the element at position i in the mutable list v.

def pop![a, r](v: MutList[a, r]): Option[a] & r

Optionally removes and returns the last element in the given mutable list v.

def product[r](v: MutList[Int32, r]): Int32 & r

Returns the product of all elements in the mutable list v.

def productWith[a, ef, ef, r](f: a -> Int32 & ef \ ef', v: MutList[a, r]): Int32 & ef and r

Returns the product of all elements in the mutable list v according to the function f.

def push![a, r](x: a, v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r

Inserts the given element x at the end of the given mutable list v.

def pushAll![m, a, r](m: m[a], v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r with Foldable[m]

Appends m to v i.e. inserts all elements from m into the end of v.

def range[r](r: Region[r], b: Int32, e: Int32): MutList[Int32, r] & r

Returns a mutable list of all integers between b (inclusive) and e (exclusive).

Returns an empty mutable list if b >= e.

def reduceLeft[a, ef, ef, r](f: a -> (a -> a & ef \ ef'), v: MutList[a, r]): Option[a] & ef and r

Applies f to all elements in v going from left to right until a single value v is obtained. Returns Some(v).

Returns None if v is empty.

def reduceRight[a, ef, ef, r](f: a -> (a -> a & ef \ ef'), v: MutList[a, r]): Option[a] & ef and r

Applies f to all elements in v going from right to left until a single value v is obtained. Returns Some(v).

Returns None if v is empty.

def remove![a, r](i: Int32, v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r

Removes the element at the given position i in the given mutable list v.

Shifts elements as necessary. Possibly expensive operation.

If the given index i exceeds the length of the mutable list, no element is removed.

def replace![a, r](from: { from = a }, to: { to = a }, v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r with Eq[a]

Replaces all occurrences of the from with to in the given mutable list v.

def reserve![a, r](n: Int32, v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r

Increases the capacity of the given mutable list v by at least n.

That is, after the call, the mutable list is guaranteed to have space for at least n additional elements.

The content of the mutable list is unchanged.

def retain![a, r](f: a -> Bool, v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r

Removes all elements from the given mutable list v that do not satisfy the given predicate f.

def reverse![a, r](v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r

Reverses the order of the elements in the given mutable list v.

def sameElements[a, r1, r2](v1: MutList[a, r1], v2: MutList[a, r2]): Bool & r1 and r2 with Eq[a]

Returns true if the mutable lists v1 and v2 have the same elements in the same order, i.e. are structurally equal.

def scan[b, a, ef, ef, r](f: b -> (a -> b & ef \ ef'), s: b, v: MutList[a, r]): MutList[b, r] & ef and r and r

Alias for scanLeft.

Accumulates the result of applying f to v going left to right.

def scanRight[a, b, ef, ef, r](f: a -> (b -> b & ef \ ef'), s: b, v: MutList[a, r]): MutList[b, r] & ef and r and r

Accumulates the result of applying f to v going right to left.

def shrink![a, r](v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r

Shrinks the given mutable list v to its actual size.

def shuffle[r1, a](r1: Region[r1], rnd: Random, v: MutList[a, r1]): MutList[a, r1] & false

Shuffles v using the Fisher–Yates shuffle.

def sort[a, r](v: MutList[a, r]): MutList[a, r] & r with Order[a]

Returns a sorted copy of MutList v, where the elements are ordered from low to high according to their Order instance.

The sort is not stable, i.e., equal elements may appear in a different order than in the input v.

The sort implementation is a Quicksort.

def sort![a, r](v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r with Order[a]

Sort MutList v so that elements are ordered from low to high according to their Order instance. The MutList is mutated in-place.

The sort is not stable, i.e., equal elements may appear in a different order than in the input v.

The sort implementation is a Quicksort.

def sortBy[a, b, r](f: a -> b, v: MutList[a, r]): MutList[a, r] & r with Order[b]

Returns a sorted copy of MutList v, where the elements are ordered from low to high according to the Order instance for the values obtained by applying f to each element.

The sort is not stable, i.e., equal elements may appear in a different order than in the input v.

The sort implementation is a Quicksort.

def sortBy![a, b, r](f: a -> b, v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r with Order[b]

Sort MutList v so that elements are ordered from low to high according to the Order instance for the values obtained by applying f to each element. The MutList is mutated in-place.

The sort is not stable, i.e., equal elements may appear in a different order than in the input v.

The sort implementation is a Quicksort.

def sortWith[a, r](cmp: a -> (a -> Comparison), v: MutList[a, r]): MutList[a, r] & r

Returns a sorted copy of MutList v, where the elements are ordered from low to high according to the comparison function cmp.

The sort is not stable, i.e., equal elements may appear in a different order than in the input v.

The sort implementation is a Quicksort.

def sortWith![a, r](cmp: a -> (a -> Comparison), v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r

Sort MutList v so that elements are ordered from low to high according to the comparison function cmp. The MutList is mutated in-place.

The sort is not stable, i.e., equal elements may appear in a different order than in the input v.

The sort implementation is a Quicksort.

def sum[r](v: MutList[Int32, r]): Int32 & r

Returns the sum of all elements in the MutList v.

def sumWith[a, ef, ef, r](f: a -> Int32 & ef \ ef', v: MutList[a, r]): Int32 & ef and r

Returns the sum of all elements in the MutList v according to the function f.

Returns v as an array.

def toChain[a, r](xs: MutList[a, r]): Chain[a] & r

Returns the mutable list xs as a chain.

def toList[a, r](v: MutList[a, r]): List[a] & r

Returns v as an immutable list.

def toMutDeque[r1, a, r2](r1: Region[r1], v: MutList[a, r2]): MutDeque[a, r1] & r2 and r1

Returns v as a MutDeque.

Apply f to every element in v.

def transformWithIndex![a, r](f: Int32 -> (a -> a), v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r

Apply f to every element in v along with that element's index.

def truncate![a, r](l: Int32, v: MutList[a, r]): Unit & r

Truncates the given mutable list v to the given length l.

That is, after the operation, the mutable list has length at most l.

If the given length l is negative, all elements are removed.

Updates the mutable map m with k -> f(v) if k -> v is in m.

Otherwise leaves the map is unchanged.

Otherwise leaves the map is unchanged.

Returns the number of mappings in the mutable map m that satisfy the predicate function f.

Purity reflective: Runs in parallel when given a pure function f.

Returns true if and only if at least one mapping in the mutable map m satisfies the predicate function f.

Returns false if m is the empty map.

def find[k, v, r](f: k -> (v -> Bool), m: MutMap[k, v, r]): Option[(k, v)] & r

Alias for findLeft.

The function f must be pure.

def findLeft[k, v, r](f: k -> (v -> Bool), m: MutMap[k, v, r]): Option[(k, v)] & r

Optionally returns the first mapping of the mutable map m that satisfies the predicate function f when searching from left to right.

The function f must be pure.

def findRight[k, v, r](f: k -> (v -> Bool), m: MutMap[k, v, r]): Option[(k, v)] & r

The function f must be pure.

def foldLeft[b, v, ef, ef, k, r](f: b -> (v -> b & ef \ ef'), i: b, m: MutMap[k, v, r]): b & ef and r

Applies f to a start value i and all values in the mutable map m going from left to right.

That is, the result is of the form: f(...f(f(i, v1), v2)..., vn).

def foldLeftWithKey[b, k, v, ef, ef, r](f: b -> (k -> (v -> b & ef \ ef')), i: b, m: MutMap[k, v, r]): b & ef and r

Applies f to a start value i and all key-value pairs in the mutable map m going from left to right.

That is, the result is of the form: f(...f(k2, f(k1, i, v1), v2)..., vn).

def foldRight[v, b, ef, ef, k, r](f: v -> (b -> b & ef \ ef'), s: b, m: MutMap[k, v, r]): b & ef and r

Applies f to a start value s and all values in the mutable map m going from right to left.

That is, the result is of the form: f(v1, ...f(vn-1, f(vn, s))).

def foldRightWithCont[v, ef, ef, b, k, r](f: v -> ((Unit -> b & ef \ ef') -> b & ef \ ef'), z: b, m: MutMap[k, v, r]): b & ef and r

Applies f to a start value z and all values in the mutable map m going from right to left.

That is, the result is of the form: f(v1, ...f(vn-1, f(vn, z))). A foldRightWithCont allows early termination by not calling the continuation.

def foldRightWithKey[k, v, b, ef, ef, r](f: k -> (v -> (b -> b & ef \ ef')), s: b, m: MutMap[k, v, r]): b & ef and r

Applies f to a start value s and all key-value pairs in the mutable map m going from right to left.

That is, the result is of the form: f(k1, v1, ...f(kn-1, vn-1, f(kn, vn, s))).

def foldRightWithKeyCont[k, v, ef, ef, b, r](f: k -> (v -> ((Unit -> b & ef \ ef') -> b & ef \ ef')), z: b, m: MutMap[k, v, r]): b & ef and r

Applies f to a start value z and all key-value pairs in the mutable map m going from right to left.

That is, the result is of the form: f(k1, v1, ...f(kn-1, vn-1, f(kn, vn, z))). A foldRightWithKeyCont allows early termination by not calling the continuation.

That is, the result is a list of all pairs (k, v) where p(k) returns Equal.

def reduceLeft[v, ef, ef, k, r](f: v -> (v -> v & ef \ ef'), m: MutMap[k, v, r]): Option[v] & ef and r

Applies f to all values in the mutable map m going from left to right until a single value v is obtained. Returns Some(v).

That is, the result is of the form: Some(f(...f(f(v1, v2), v3)..., vn))

Returns None if m is the empty map.

def reduceLeftWithKey[k, v, ef, ef, r](f: k -> (v -> (k -> (v -> (k, v) & ef \ ef'))), m: MutMap[k, v, r]): Option[(k, v)] & ef and r

Applies f to all mappings in the mutable map m going from left to right until a single mapping (k, v) is obtained. Returns Some((k, v)).

That is, the result is of the form: Some(f(...f(f(k1, v1, k2, v2), k3, v3)..., kn, vn))

Returns None if m is the empty map.

def reduceRight[v, ef, ef, k, r](f: v -> (v -> v & ef \ ef'), m: MutMap[k, v, r]): Option[v] & ef and r

Applies f to all values in the mutable map m going from right to left until a single value v is obtained. Returns Some(v).

That is, the result is of the form: Some(f(v1, ...f(vn-2, f(vn-1, vn))...))

Returns None if m is the empty map.

def reduceRightWithKey[k, v, ef, ef, r](f: k -> (v -> (k -> (v -> (k, v) & ef \ ef'))), m: MutMap[k, v, r]): Option[(k, v)] & ef and r

Applies f to all mappings in the mutable map m going from right to left until a single mapping (k, v) is obtained. Returns Some((k, v)).

That is, the result is of the form: Some(f(k1, v1, ...f(kn-2, vn-2, f(kn-1, vn-1, kn, vn))...))

Returns None if m is the empty map.

Nec

Enums

enum ViewLeft[a: Type] with Eq
case OneLeft(a)
case SomeLeft((a, Nec[a]))
enum ViewRight[a: Type] with Eq
case OneRight(a)
case SomeRight((Nec[a], a))

A datatype for pattern matching on a Nec (traversing right-to-left).

Definitions

def ap[a, ef, ef, b](f: Nec[a -> b & ef \ ef'], c: Nec[a]): Nec[b] & ef

Apply every function from f to every argument from x and return a Nec with all results. For f = f1, f2, ... and x = x1, x2, ... the results appear in the order f1(x1), f1(x2), ..., f2(x1), f2(x2), ....

def reduceRightTo[a, b, ef1, ef1, ef2, ef2](f: a -> (b -> b & ef1 \ ef1'), g: a -> b & ef2 \ ef2', c: Nec[a]): b & ef1 and ef2

Right-associative reduction of a structure. Applies g to the initial element of c and combines it with the remainder of c using f going from right to left.

def replace[a](from: { from = a }, to: { to = a }, l: Nec[a]): Nec[a] & true with Eq[a]

Returns l with every occurrence of from replaced by to.

def reverse[a](c: Nec[a]): Nec[a] & true

Returns the reverse of c.

def sequence[m, a](c: Nec[m[a]]): m[Nec[a]] & true with Applicative[m]

Returns the result of running all the actions in the Nec c.

def shuffle[a](rnd: Random, c: Nec[a]): Option[Nec[a]] & false

Optionally returns the Nec c shuffled using the Fisher–Yates shuffle.

def singleton[a](x: a): Nec[a] & true

Return the singleton Nec with element x.

def snoc[a](c: Nec[a], x: a): Nec[a] & true

Add element x to the right end of Nec c.

def sort[a](c: Nec[a]): Nec[a] & true with Order[a]

Sort Nec c so that elements are ordered from low to high according to their Order instance.

The sort is not stable, i.e., equal elements may appear in a different order than in the input c.

The sort implementation is a Quicksort.

def sortBy[a, b](f: a -> b, c: Nec[a]): Nec[a] & true with Order[b]

Sort Nec c so that elements are ordered from low to high according to the Order instance for the values obtained by applying f to each element.

The sort is not stable, i.e., equal elements may appear in a different order than in the input c.

The sort implementation is a Quicksort.

def sortWith[a](cmp: a -> (a -> Comparison), c: Nec[a]): Nec[a] & true

Sort Nec c so that elements are ordered from low to high according to the comparison function cmp.

The sort is not stable, i.e., equal elements may appear in a different order than in the input c.

The sort implementation is a Quicksort.

def subsequences[a](c: Nec[a]): Nec[List[a]] & true

Returns all subsequences of l in lexicographical order by element indices in l.

That is, l is the first subsequence and Nil is the last subsequence.

Returns the sum of all elements in the Nec c.

If c contains multiple mappings with the same key, toMap does not make any guarantees about which mapping will be in the resulting map.

def unzip[a, b](c: Nec[(a, b)]): (Nec[a], Nec[b]) & true

Returns a pair of Necs, the first containing all first components in c and the second containing all second components in c.

def viewLeft[a](c: Nec[a]): ViewLeft[a] & true

Deconstruct a Nec from left-to-right.

Returns SomeLeft(x, rs) if the Nec has at least two elements, where x is the leftmost element of the Nec c, and rs is the rest of the Nec.

Returns OneLeft if the Nec has a single element.

def viewRight[a](c: Nec[a]): ViewRight[a] & true

Deconstruct a Nec from right-to-left.

Returns SomeRight(rs, x) if the Nec has at least two elements, where x is the rightmost element of the Nec c, and rs is the front of the Nec.

Returns OneRight if the Nec has a single element.

def zip[a, b](c1: Nec[a], c2: Nec[b]): Nec[(a, b)] & true

Returns a Nec where the element at index i is (a, b) where a is the element at index i in c1 and b is the element at index i in c2.

If either c1 or c2 becomes depleted, then no further elements are added to the resulting Nec.

def zipWith[a, b, ef, ef, c](f: a -> (b -> c & ef \ ef'), c1: Nec[a], c2: Nec[b]): Nec[c] & ef

Returns a Nec where the element at index i is f(a, b) where a is the element at index i in c1 and b is the element at index i in c2.

If either c1 or c2 becomes depleted, then no further elements are added to the resulting Nec.

Generalize zipWith to an applicative functor f.

Returns a Nec where each element e is mapped to (e, i) where i is the index of e.

def ap[a, ef, ef, b](f: Nel[a -> b & ef \ ef'], l: Nel[a]): Nel[b] & ef

Apply every function from f to every argument from l and return a non-empty list with all results. For f = f1, f2, ... and x = x1, x2, ... the results appear in the order f1(x1), f1(x2), ..., f2(x1), f2(x2), ....

That is, the result is of the form: f(x1, ...f(xn-1, f(xn, z))...). A foldRightWithCont allows early termination by not calling the continuation.

Definitions

def ap[a, ef, ef, b](f: Option[a -> b & ef \ ef'], x: Option[a]): Option[b] & ef

If both arguments are Some, return a Some containing the result of applying the function inside f to the value inside x. Otherwise return None.

Returns 1 if o is Some(v) and the predicate f(v) evaluates to true. Otherwise returns 0.

def foldLeftM[b, a, ef, ef](f: b -> (a -> Option[b] & ef \ ef'), s: b, l: List[a]): Option[b] & ef

Returns the result of applying f to a start value s and the elements in l going from left to right.

If at any step applying f fails (i.e. it produces a None value) the traversal of l is short-circuited and None is returned.

If f is successfully applied to all the elements in l the result is of the form: Some(f(...f(f(s, x1), x2)..., xn)).

def foldMap[a, ef, ef, b](f: a -> b & ef \ ef', o: Option[a]): b & ef with Monoid[b]

Returns the result of mapping each element and combining the results.

Returns f(v, z) if o is Some(v). Otherwise returns z.

def foldRightM[a, b, ef, ef](f: a -> (b -> Option[b] & ef \ ef'), s: b, l: List[a]): Option[b] & ef

Returns the result of applying f to a start value s and the elements in l going from right to left.

If at any step applying f fails (i.e. it produces a None value) the traversal of l is short-circuited and None is returned.

If f is successfully applied to al elements in l the result is of the form: Some(f(x1, ...f(xn-1, f(xn, s))...)).

def foldRightWithCont[a, ef, ef, b](f: a -> ((Unit -> b & ef \ ef') -> b & ef \ ef'), o: Option[a], z: b): b & ef

Returns f(v, z) if o is Some(v). Otherwise returns z.

A foldRightWithCont allows early termination by not calling the continuation.

RedBlackTree

Enums

enum Color[]
case Red(Unit)
case Black(Unit)
case DoubleBlack(Unit)

The color of a red-black tree node.

enum RedBlackTree[k: Type, v: Type] with Sendable
case Leaf(Unit)
case DoubleBlackLeaf(Unit)
case Node((Color, RedBlackTree[k, v], k, v, RedBlackTree[k, v]))

An immutable red-black tree implementation with keys of type k and values of type v.

A red-black tree is a self-balancing binary search tree. Each node is either red or black, although a transitory color double-black is allowed during deletion. The red-black tree satisfy the following invariants.

  1. For all nodes with key x, the left subtree contains only nodes with keys y < x and the right subtree contains only nodes with keys z > x.
  2. No red node has a red parent.
  3. Every path from the root to a leaf contains the same number of black nodes.

Definitions

def blackHeight[k, v](t: RedBlackTree[k, v]): Int32 & true

Returns the black height of t.

def empty[k, v](_unit: Unit): RedBlackTree[k, v] & true

Returns the empty tree.

def exists[k, v, ef, ef](f: k -> (v -> Bool & ef \ ef'), t: RedBlackTree[k, v]): Bool & ef

Returns true if and only if at least one key-value pair in t satisfies the predicate f.

Returns false if t is the empty tree.

def filter[v, ef, ef, k](f: v -> Bool & ef \ ef', t: RedBlackTree[k, v]): RedBlackTree[k, v] & ef with Order[k]

Returns a new copy of tree t with just the nodes that satisfy the predicate f.

def filterMap[a, ef, ef, b, k](f: a -> Option[b] & ef \ ef', t: RedBlackTree[k, a]): RedBlackTree[k, b] & ef with Order[k]

Collects the results of applying the partial function f to every element in t. This traverses tree t and produces a new tree with just nodes where applying f produces Some(_).

def findLeft[k, v, ef, ef](f: k -> (v -> Bool & ef \ ef'), t: RedBlackTree[k, v]): Option[(k, v)] & ef

Optionally returns the first key-value pair in t that satisfies the predicate f when searching from left to right.

def findRight[k, v, ef, ef](f: k -> (v -> Bool & ef \ ef'), t: RedBlackTree[k, v]): Option[(k, v)] & ef

Optionally returns the first key-value pair in t that satisfies the predicate f when searching from right to left.

def foldLeft[b, k, v, ef, ef](f: b -> (k -> (v -> b & ef \ ef')), s: b, t: RedBlackTree[k, v]): b & ef

Applies f to a start value s and all key-value pairs in t going from left to right.

That is, the result is of the form: f(...f(f(s, k1, v1), k2, v2)..., vn).

def foldMap[k, v, ef, ef, b](f: k -> (v -> b & ef \ ef'), t: RedBlackTree[k, v]): b & ef with Monoid[b]

Returns the result of mapping each key-value pair and combining the results.

def foldRight[k, v, b, ef, ef](f: k -> (v -> (b -> b & ef \ ef')), s: b, t: RedBlackTree[k, v]): b & ef

Applies f to a start value s and all key-value pairs in tree going from right to left.

That is, the result is of the form: f(k1, v1, ...f(kn-1, vn-1, f(kn, vn, s))).

def foldRightWithCont[k, v, ef, ef, b](f: k -> (v -> ((Unit -> b & ef \ ef') -> b & ef \ ef')), z: b, t: RedBlackTree[k, v]): b & ef

Applies f to a start value z and all key-value pairs in t going from right to left.

That is, the result is of the form: f(k1, v1, ...f(kn-1, vn-1, f(kn, vn, s))). A foldRightWithCont allows early termination by not calling the continuation.

Returns true if and only if all key-value pairs in t satisfy the predicate f.

def foldLeftM[b, a, ef, ef, e](f: b -> (a -> Result[b, e] & ef \ ef'), s: b, l: List[a]): Result[b, e] & ef

Returns the result of applying f to a start value s and the elements in l going from left to right.

If at any step applying f fails (i.e. it produces a Err(e) value) the traversal of l is short-circuited and Err(e) is returned.

If f is successfully applied to all elements in l the result is of the form: Ok(f(...f(f(s, x1), x2)..., xn)).

def foldRight[t, a, ef, ef, e](f: t -> (a -> a & ef \ ef'), z: a, r: Result[t, e]): a & ef

Returns f(v, z) if r is Ok(v). Otherwise returns z.

def foldRightM[a, b, ef, ef, e](f: a -> (b -> Result[b, e] & ef \ ef'), s: b, l: List[a]): Result[b, e] & ef

Returns the result of applying f to a start value s and the elements in l going from right to left.

If at any step applying f fails (i.e. it produces a Err(e) value) the traversal of l is short-circuited and Err(e) is returned.

If f is successfully applied to all elements in l the result is of the form: Ok(f(x1, ...f(xn-1, f(xn, s))...)).

def foldRightWithCont[t, ef, ef, a, e](f: t -> ((Unit -> a & ef \ ef') -> a & ef \ ef'), z: a, r: Result[t, e]): a & ef

Returns f(v, z) if r is Ok(v). Otherwise returns z.

def abbreviateLeft[](w: Int32, s: String): String & true

Abbreviate the string s if it exceeds the width w.

If the length of s exceeds w and w >= 3" then s` is truncated and the first three characters are replaced with ellipses.

If the length of s exceeds w and `w < 3" then the empty string is returned.

def abbreviateRight[](w: Int32, s: String): String & true

Abbreviate the string s if it exceeds the width w.

If the length of s exceeds w and w >= 3" then s` is truncated and the last three characters are replaced with ellipses.

If the length of s exceeds w and `w < 3" then the empty string is returned.

def patch[](i: Int32, n: Int32, sub: String, s: String): String & true

Returns s with the n elements starting at index i replaced with the elements of sub.

If any of the indices i, i+1, i+2, ... , i+n-1 are out of range in s then no patching is done at these indices. If s becomes depleted then no further patching is done. If patching occurs at index i+j in s, then the element at index j in sub is used.

def repeat[](n: Int32, s: String): String & true

Returns a string with the string s repeated n times.

Returns the empty string if n < 0.

def replace[](from: { from = String }, to: { to = String }, s: String): String & true

Returns s with every match of the substring from replaced by the string to.

def replaceChar[](from: { from = Char }, to: { to = Char }, s: String): String & true

Returns s with every match of the character target replaced by the character rep.

def replaceFirstMatch[](regex: { regex = String }, to: { to = String }, s: String): String & true

Returns s with the first match of the regular expression regex replaced by the string to.

def replaceMatches[](regex: { regex = String }, to: { to = String }, s: String): String & true

Returns s with every match of the regular expression regex replaced by the string to.

def reverse[](s: String): String & true

Returns the reverse of s.

def rotateLeft[](n: Int32, s: String): String & true

Rotate the contents of string s by n steps to the left.

def rotateRight[](n: Int32, s: String): String & true

Rotate the contents of string s by n steps to the right.

def slice[](b: Int32, e: Int32, s: String): String & true

Returns the substring of s from index b (inclusive) to index e (exclusive).

If b or e are out-of-bounds, return the empty string.

def sliceLeft[](e: Int32, s: String): String & true

Get the substring of s to the left of index e (exclusive).

sliceLeft == slice(0 , e, s)

def sliceRight[](b: Int32, s: String): String & true

Get the substring of s to the right starting at index b (inclusive).

sliceRight == slice(b , length(s), s)

def split[](regex: { regex = String }, s: String): List[String] & true

Splits the string s around matches of the regular expression regex.

def splitAt[](n: Int32, s: String): (String, String) & true

Split the string s at the position n returning the left and right parts.

If n exceeds the length of string s, return the whole string paired with the empty string.

def splitOn[](substr: { substr = String }, s: String): List[String] & true

Split the string s on matches of substr.

def startsWith[](prefix: { prefix = String }, s: String): Bool & true

Returns true if the string s starts with the string prefix.

def stripIndent[](n: Int32, s: String): String & true

Strip every indented line in string s by n spaces. n must be greater than 0. Note, tabs are counted as a single space.

If the string s in nonempty, the returned string normalizes line termination characters and adds a line terminator to the last line of the string if it does not already end with a newline.

If the string s is empty, then the empty string is returned.

def stripPrefix[](substr: { substr = String }, s: String): Option[String] & true

Returns Some(suffix) of string s if its prefix matches substr.

def stripSuffix[](substr: { substr = String }, s: String): Option[String] & true

Returns Some(prefix) of string s if its suffix matches substr.

def take[](n: Int32, s: String): String & true

Alias for takeLeft.

def takeLeft[](n: Int32, s: String): String & true

Take the first n characters of string s from the left.

If n extends past the end of string s, return all the characters of s.

def takeRight[](n: Int32, s: String): String & true

Take the last n characters of string s from the right.

If n is greater than the length of string s, return all the characters of s.

def takeWhile[](f: Char -> Bool, s: String): String & true

Alias for takeWileLeft.

def takeWhileLeft[](f: Char -> Bool, s: String): String & true

Returns the initial prefix of string s where all the chars satisfy the predicate f.

The function f must be pure.

def takeWhileRight[](f: Char -> Bool, s: String): String & true

Returns the suffix of string s where all the characters satisfy the predicate f.

The function f must be pure.

def toArray[r](r: Region[r], s: String): Array[Char, r] & r

Returns the given string s as an array of characters.

def toChunks[](k: Int32, s: String): List[String] & true

Split the string s into chunks of length k, the last chunk may be smaller than k.

k should be greater than 0.

def toList[](s: String): List[Char] & true

Returns the given string s as a list of characters.

def toLowerCase[](s: String): String & true

Returns the lower case version of the string s.

def toUpperCase[](s: String): String & true

Returns the upper case version of the string s.

def trim[](s: String): String & true

Returns a copy of the string s without trailing and leading whitespaces.

Returns a new empty string if there is no characters in s.

def trimLeft[](s: String): String & true

Returns string s with all leading space characters removed.

def trimRight[](s: String): String & true

Returns string s with all trailing space characters removed.

def unfold[b, ef, ef](f: b -> Option[(Char, b)] & ef \ ef', x: b): String & ef

Build a string from the seed value x applying the function f until f returns None.

def unfoldString[b, ef, ef](f: b -> Option[(String, b)] & ef \ ef', x: b): String & ef

Build a string from the seed value x applying the function f until f returns None.

This is a version of unfold where f generates substrings rather than chars.

def unfoldStringWithIter[ef, ef](f: Unit -> Option[String] & ef \ ef'): String & ef

Build a string by applying the function next to (). next is expected to encapsulate a stateful resource such as a file handle that can be iterated.

next should return Some(s) to signal a new substring s.

next should return None to signal the end of building the string.

def unfoldWithIter[ef, ef](f: Unit -> Option[Char] & ef \ ef'): String & ef

Build a string by applying the function next to (). next is expected to encapsulate a stateful resource such as a file handle that can be iterated.

next should return Some(c) to signal a new char c.

next should return None to signal the end of building the string.

def unlines[](a: List[String]): String & true

Join the list of strings a separating each pair of strings and ending the result string with the system dependent line separator.

def unwords[](l: List[String]): String & true

Join the array of strings l separating each pair of strings with a single space character.

def update[](i: Int32, a: Char, s: String): String & true

Returns s with the element at index i replaced by a.

Returns s if i < 0 or i > length(xs)-1.

def words[](s: String): List[String] & true

Split the string s into an list of words, dividing on one or more white space characters. Leading and trailing spaces are trimmed.

def zip[](a: String, b: String): List[(Char, Char)] & true

Returns an array where the element at index i is (x, y) where x is the element at index i in a and y is the element at index i in b.

If either a or b becomes depleted, then no further elements are added to the resulting array.

def zipWith[ef, ef](f: Char -> (Char -> Char & ef \ ef'), a: String, b: String): String & ef

Returns a string where the element at index i is f(x, y) where x is the element at index i in a and y is the element at index i in b.

If either a or b becomes depleted, then no further elements are added to the resulting array.

System/StdIn

Definitions

def readLines[](_unit: Unit): Iterator[String, Static] & false

Returns an iterator over lines from the standard input stream.

The iterator ends when the stream is closed or when an error occurs.

When the iterator is garbage collected the standard input stream is closed. Thus, the readLines function should not be called more than once per program.

See also Console.readLine for reading from the console.

Traversable

Definitions

def for[t, a, ef, ef, m, b](t: t[a], f: a -> m[b] & ef \ ef'): m[t[b]] & ef with Applicative[m], Traversable[t]

Returns the result of applying the applicative mapping function f to all the elements of the data structure t.

for is traverse with it's arguments flipped.

def mapAccumLeft[acc, a, ef, ef, b, t](f: acc -> (a -> (acc, b) & ef \ ef'), start: acc, t: t[a]): (acc, t[b]) & ef with Traversable[t]

Returns the result of applying f to the traversable structure t and the initial state acc. The result is a pair of the final state and the updated copy of the structure.

mapAccumLeft is essentially the combination of map and foldLeft - like map it returns an updated copy of the initial structure, like foldLeft it passes an updating accumulator through each step of the traversal.

Validation

Definitions

Applies the function in v1 to the value in v2.

def exists[t, ef, ef, e](f: t -> Bool & ef \ ef', v: Validation[t, e]): Bool & ef

Returns true if and only if v is Success(t) and f(t) is true.

Returns false if v is Failure.

Returns true if v is Success(t) and f(t) is true or if v is Failure.

Returns t if v is Success(t). Otherwise returns d.

def lift10[t1, t2, t3, t4, t5, t6, t7, t8, t9, t10, ef, ef, u, e](f: t1 -> (t2 -> (t3 -> (t4 -> (t5 -> (t6 -> (t7 -> (t8 -> (t9 -> (t10 -> u & ef \ ef'))))))))), v1: Validation[t1, e], v2: Validation[t2, e], v3: Validation[t3, e], v4: Validation[t4, e], v5: Validation[t5, e], v6: Validation[t6, e], v7: Validation[t7, e], v8: Validation[t8, e], v9: Validation[t9, e], v10: Validation[t10, e]): Validation[u, e] & ef

Returns Success(f(v)) if o is Success(v). Otherwise returns v.

def sequence[t, e](l: List[Validation[t, e]]): Validation[List[t], e] & true

Returns Success(v1 :: v2 :: ... :: vn) if each of l_i is Success(v_i).

Otherwise returns Failure(e1 :: ... :: en) with all of the failures concatenated.

def toList[t, e](v: Validation[t, e]): List[t] & true

Converts a Validation to a List.

Returns t :: Nil if v is Success(v). Returns Nil if v is Failure(e).

def toOption[t, e](v: Validation[t, e]): Option[t] & true

Converts a Validation to an Option.

Returns Some(t) if v is Success(t). Returns None otherwise.

def toResult[t, e](v: Validation[t, e]): Result[t, Nec[e]] & true

Converts a Validation to a Result.

Returns Ok(t) if v is Success(t). Returns Err(e) if v is Failure(e).

def traverse[a, ef, ef, b, e](f: a -> Validation[b, e] & ef \ ef', l: List[a]): Validation[List[b], e] & ef

Returns Success(v1 :: v2 :: ... v :: vn) if each of f(l_i) is Success(v_i).

Otherwise returns Failure(e1 :: ... :: en) with all of the failures concatenated.

def traverseX[a, ef, ef, b, e](f: a -> Validation[b, e] & ef \ ef', l: List[a]): Validation[Unit, e] & ef

Returns Success() if each of f(l_i) is Success(_).

Otherwise returns Failure(e1 :: ... :: en) with all of the failures concatenated.

This function is the "forgetful" version of traverse, use it when the you want the effect of applying f to each element but do not care about collecting the results.

def withDefault[t, e](default: { default = Validation[t, e] }, v: Validation[t, e]): Validation[t, e] & true

Returns v if it is Success(v). Otherwise returns default.
